e ResponseMessage handling and class name match the source. ✓\n\ns2 validates the Maven dependency reference. ✓\n\ns3 checks out on both the messaging_context_handler ordering constraint and the two-phase commit scenarios, with the source using slightly different wording but conveying the same meaning about message queue operations. ✓\n\ns4 verifies the StandardFwHeaderDefinition default, XML configuration example, and the reference to mom_system_messaging all align with the source material. ✓\n\nNow I'm checking the RST heading structure in the source document. The main sections use consistent h2-level headings with 50-dash underlines, though I'm noticing the 制約 section appears to use a shorter underline that I need to count more carefully to confirm the exact formatting pattern. Now I'm checking the hints for completeness across each section. For s1, I see hints covering MessageReplyHandler and ResponseMessage, but I notice the full class name `nablarch.fw.messaging.ResponseMessage` isn't included in the hints even though it appears explicitly in the source content—that's a gap I should flag. I'm noticing that s2 is missing PascalCase class names in its hints, while s3 and s4 have adequate coverage of their key concepts. The main gap I'm seeing is that s1 should include the fully qualified name `nablarch.fw.messaging.ResponseMessage` since it's referenced in the source material and documented in the official Javadoc URLs. Looking more carefully at the hints across different sections, I notice s4 includes both the simple class name and fully qualified name for `StandardFwHeaderDefinition`, and s1 has the FQN for `MessageReplyHandler`, but `ResponseMessage` only appears as the simple name without its fully qualified counterpart `nablarch.fw.messaging.ResponseMessage`. This is a minor completeness gap in the hints.\n\nReviewing the s3 content about two-phase commits, the source explains that when using two-phase commit, both database and message queue transactions are committed together by the transaction manager, which means the response message must be sent before transaction control—so this handler needs to be positioned after the transaction management handler. The knowledge file is otherwise solid with just this one minor hints issue to address. I found one minor discrepancy worth noting—the FQN hint is missing from the knowledge file version.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13792,"cache_read_input_tokens":18400,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":13792,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57fcd945-0b88-4a21-b962-74d54cfff5ef","uuid":"eb7538bf-e15d-4143-bd2a-af6561e2baa6"}
